 of Swedish   Bengtsson  . Compare   Bankson  .","History: Andrew Bankston, alias Anders Bengtsson, came to New Sweden on the Delaware river in 1656; he died in Philadelphia, PA, in 1706."]},{"name":"Bengston","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Helmer, Nels, Nils.","Altered (metathesized) form of Swedish   Bengtsson  ."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bankson","meanings":["Americanized form of Swedish   Bengtsson  . Compare   Bankston  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357046,"age":63,"year":"1250","julianDay":2177614,"description":"King Eriksson died. Valdemar crowned King. Birger Jarl declared regent until Valdemar is of age.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1702074,"age":65,"year":"1252","julianDay":2178344,"title":"Earliest Mention of Stockholm","description":"The earliest known recorded history of the city of Stockholm is in Norse sagas as Agnafit which dates to 1252. The city rose to prominence due to Baltic trade. Stockholm is now the most populous urban area in the region.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1357047,"age":79,"year"